	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>USDA annual review of the EU cereals sector</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 May 2009
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The USDA has posted its 2009 annual review of the EU cereals sector. It notes that following a record crop in 2008/09 ‘this year’s total EU grain crop is currently forecast to decline 23 million metric tonnes to 290 million metric tonnes’. However, ‘this is still over 15 million metric tonnes more than forecast domestic grain consumption in 2009/10’. Weather conditions and tighter market conditions contributed to this decline. The land area under cereals is forecast to be 3% down on last year. This is attributed to weather-related factors and is not linked to any recent policy developments. Yields are also expected to be down.</p><p>Feed-grain consumption is forecast to fall as the reduction in herd size continues. However grain use in biofuels is forecast to increase. Given increased competition on overseas markets, EU stocks are expected to increase significantly (+ 19 million tonnes to 47.8 million tonnes), despite good export prospects. </p><p>At the policy level the USDA analysis notes the abandonment of set-aside as a policy tool. The EU is now also limiting intervention buying, with this being set at zero for durum wheat, rice (2009/10), barley and sorghum (2010/11). For soft wheat intervention purchases between November 1st and May 31st will be possible, up to a ceiling of 3 million tonnes. Intervention for maize is being phased out from 2009/10, having been subject to a ceiling of 1.5 million tonnes in 2007/08 and 700,000 tonnes in 2008/09. While intervention levels are being set at zero, the continued availability of this policy tool should be noted.</p><p>The USDA analysis highlights the ongoing decoupling of payments in the cereals sector. Payments for durum wheat and hops will be decoupled by January 1st 2010, while decoupling for dried fodder will be completed by April 1st 2012, with the process being completed for protein crops in the course of 2012. A review of the state of play will then be completed before the end of the 2012.</p><p>The rate of ‘modulation’, the reclaiming of part of the payments made to farmers in excess of €5,000 per annum for use in financing additional rural-development initiatives, will increase to 7% in 2009, 8% in 2010, 9% in 20111 and 10% in 2012. In addition a supplementary progressive modulation impacting on large holdings that receive over €300,000 in direct aid is to be introduced. The rate of progressive modulation is set at 4% over and above the increases applicable in 2009’ (e.g. 2%+4% in 2009, 3%+4% in 2010, 4%+4% in 2011 and 5%+4% in 2012).</p><p>The USDA notes that following falls in global cereals prices, the EU reintroduced import duties in October 2008.</p><p>Looking beyond the EU the USDA has posted updates on the state of play in global cereals markets. Overall, while global production is forecast to be down compared to the preceding year, ‘it remains larger than projected consumption’. Grain stocks are also improved for 2009/10 at 85 million tonnes. These stocks will provide a buffer against smaller grain crops as consumption continues to grow. This should serve to ease future price pressures. </p><p>Global wheat production will be 25 million tonnes down on last year (at 658 million tonnes), on the back of a 1% decline in the area planted in response to high input costs. ‘Global consumption is projected to expand to 643 million tonnes’ 7 million tonnes higher than the preceding year. Expanded feed use accounted for much of last year’s consumption growth and while this is expected to decline this year, it will still be large by historical standards. However global stocks are expected to rise, easing price pressures. Indeed, global trade is expected to decline by 10 million tonnes compared to last year (as record year at 121.8 million tonnes), as production recovers in certain countries.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
USDA FAS<i>, GAIN Report</i>, April 30th 2009<br />
<a href="http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Commodity%20Report_EU-27%20GRAIN%20_London_United%20Kingdom%20EU-27_4-30-2009.pdf" target="_self">http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Commodity%20Report...</a></p><p>
USDA<i> </i>FAS,<i> Circular Series, </i>FG 05-09, May 2009<br />
<a href="http://www.fas.usda.gov/grain/circular/2009/05-09/grainfull05-09.pdf" target="_self">http://www.fas.usda.gov/grain/circular/2009/05-09/grainfull05-09.pdf</a></p><p>
USDA<i> </i>FAS,<i> Circular Series, </i>WAP 05-09, May 2009 <br />
<a href="http://www.fas.usda.gov/wap/circular/2009/09-05/productionfull05-09.pdf" target="_self">http://www.fas.usda.gov/wap/circular/2009/09-05/productionfull05-09.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>At the policy level it should be noted that while the EU is reducing the use of certain policy tools such as intervention buying, it is retaining the right to use such policy tools extensively, should the market situation require it. This is an important distinction to note. Thus we find that while earlier, in the face of high cereals prices, the EU had set import duties for certain cereals at zero, duty levels were subsequently raised following declines in global cereals prices. Equally, while export refunds had been set at zero during the period of high global prices, these were subsequently increased as global food prices fell.</p><p>This reduction of the use of a policy tool, when market conditions are permissive of such a move and its subsequent expanded use in response to changed market conditions, is quite a different policy framework from the abandonment of the right to use certain agricultural policy tools, which the EU is advocating in the context of the EPA negotiations. This is an important consideration for ACP negotiators to bear in mind when reviewing ‘contentious issues’ impacting on the agricultural sector.</p>
		</div>
		
